documentation.text:
In dynamic arrays the first word stores the length of data, after which comes the data.
 Example: 0x40 0x01 0x02
          ^len ^data
@dev Converts a bytes array to a slice (without copying data)
@dev Subslice a bytes array using the given start index until the end of the array (without copying data)

@dev Subslice a bytes array using the given indexes (without copying data)
 The start index is inclusive, the end index is exclusive
@dev Returns the pointer to the start of a slice
@dev Returns the slice length in bytes

@dev Copies the slice to a new bytes array
 The slice will NOT point to the new bytes array

Low-level generic implementation of tight encoding for arrays, used by codegen.
 This is the same as solidity's internal tight encoding for array data in storage.

Copies the array to a new bytes array, tightly packing it.
 elementSize is in bytes, leftPaddingBits is in bits.
 elementSize and leftPaddingBits must be correctly provided by the caller based on the array's element type.
 @return data a tightly packed array

Unpacks the slice to a new memory location and lays it out like a memory array.
 elementSize is in bytes, leftPaddingBits is in bits.
 elementSize and leftPaddingBits must be correctly provided by the caller based on the array's element type.
 @return array a generic array, needs to be casted to the expected type using assembly

Adapted from https://github.com/dk1a/solidity-stringutils/blob/main/src/utils/mem.sol#L149-L167
 @dev Left-aligned byte mask (e.g. for partial mload/mstore).
 For byteLength >= 32 returns type(uint256).max
 length 0:   0x000000...000000
 length 1:   0xff0000...000000
 length 2:   0xffff00...000000
 ...
 length 30:  0xffffff...ff0000
 length 31:  0xffffff...ffff00
 length 32+: 0xffffff...ffffff
